# Meshtastic firmware with ControlPointModule (experimental)

This release contains a custom Meshtastic firmware build that adds an
experimental routing extension based on **control points**.

The implementation is built on top of the official `meshtastic/firmware`
repository and keeps the default routing behavior (next-hop routing and
managed flooding) as a fallback.

## What is included

- `firmware-heltec-v3-<VERSION>.bin`  
  Custom firmware for **Heltec WiFi LoRa 32 V3 (ESP32-S3)** with
  `ControlPointModule` integrated into the routing pipeline.

- Standard Meshtastic helper scripts from the official release:
  - `device-install.sh` / `device-install.bat`
  - `device-update.sh` / `device-update.bat`
  - any other files required by the official Meshtastic installer

The structure of this ZIP matches the official Meshtastic ESP32 release,
so it can be used both with:
- the Meshtastic **Web Flasher** (`flasher.meshtastic.org`);
- the official CLI install scripts.

## How to flash using the Web Flasher

1. Download this **ZIP** file to your computer.  
2. Open Chrome or Edge and visit: `https://flasher.meshtastic.org`.  
3. Connect your Heltec WiFi LoRa 32 V3 via USB and put it into bootloader
   mode (press and hold BOOT, tap RESET, then release BOOT).  
4. In the Web Flasher:
   - Select your device type (Heltec WiFi LoRa 32 V3 or equivalent).
   - Instead of choosing a firmware version from the list, click the
     **folder** icon and select this ZIP file from disk.
5. Choose **Erase & Install** (recommended for switching between firmware
   variants) or **Install** if you want to keep existing settings.
6. Wait until the flashing process completes and the device reboots.

After flashing, connect with the Meshtastic app as usual and verify that
the node boots and joins the mesh.

## How this build differs from official Meshtastic

- Adds a new protobuf payload `ControlPointMessage` on the
  `PRIVATE_APP` port.
- Implements `ControlPointModule`:
  - broadcasts control-point metrics periodically;
  - stores peer metrics with TTL and basic validation;
  - provides `choosePreferredRelay()` to suggest a better next hop based
    on route cost, load, and priority.
- Integrates `ControlPointModule` into `NextHopRouter`:
  - if a valid preferred relay is available, it is used as `next_hop`;
  - otherwise, the standard Meshtastic routing (`getNextHop()` and
    managed flooding) is used as a fallback.

All low-level packet handling, ACK logic and flooding behavior remain
unchanged, so this build should stay compatible with standard Meshtastic
nodes at the packet level.

## Status and caveats

- **Experimental:** This firmware is part of an academic project exploring
  control-point-based routing heuristics. Use it on test nodes first.
- No stability guarantees. Routing decisions may differ from the stock
  firmware in non-obvious ways.
- Always keep at least one device with official Meshtastic firmware as a
  reference node in your test mesh.

If you encounter issues, please capture serial logs from the node and
include the exact commit hash / branch name used to build this release.
